    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are Holland codes (RIASEC)?</summary>
        <p>Holland codes are a career interest classification system developed by psychologist John Holland. The six types are Realistic (hands-on work), Investigative (analytical work), Artistic (creative work), Social (helping others), Enterprising (leading and persuading), and Conventional (organizing and data management). Your top two or three codes can be matched to occupations. Take our <a href="/test/career-aptitude-test/">career aptitude test</a> to discover your Holland codes.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between aptitude and interest?</summary>
        <p>Aptitude is your natural ability or potential to develop a skill, while interest is what you enjoy and find engaging. The most satisfying careers align both: you are good at the work and you find it rewarding. Career assessments that measure both dimensions provide the most complete picture of your ideal career fit, helping you avoid pursuing work you enjoy but struggle with, or work you excel at but find unfulfilling.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can a personality test really tell me what career to choose?</summary>
        <p>Personality tests cannot dictate a specific career, but they can significantly narrow the field by identifying work environments, tasks, and roles that align with your natural tendencies. Research confirms that personality-job fit predicts satisfaction and performance. However, career choice involves many factors beyond personality, so assessments are best used as one input in a broader exploration process.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is it too late to change careers?</summary>
        <p>It is rarely too late to change careers. Research shows that career changers often experience an initial income dip but typically recover within two to five years and report significantly higher job satisfaction. Many skills transfer across industries, and experience from a previous career can be a significant asset. The key is to approach the transition strategically with transferable skill identification, financial planning, and real-world testing of assumptions.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How important are values in career satisfaction?</summary>
        <p>Values are one of the most important factors in career satisfaction. Research consistently shows that alignment between personal and work values is a stronger predictor of long-term satisfaction than salary or prestige. Core work values include autonomy, achievement, relationships, security, altruism, and variety. When daily work conflicts with core values, dissatisfaction builds regardless of skill or interest alignment.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

